          {
            "allowLineSplit": true,
            "content": "Setting wrap to none makes the image purely decorative — it registers no obstacle in the SpatialMap, so not a single character of text is reflowed. Body copy renders at full column width and the image overlaps it visually. Boxes are painted in document order, so depth is controlled by child order in the story.",
            "keepWithNext": false,
            "kind": "flow-block",
            "overflowPolicy": "clip",
            "pageBreakBefore": false,
            "source": {
              "path": "elements[2].children[20]"
            },
            "sourceType": "p",
            "style": {
              "allowLineSplit": true,
              "marginBottom": 8,
              "orphans": 2,
              "widows": 2
            }
          },
          {
            "allowLineSplit": true,
            "content": "Pagination in the StoryPackager follows a split-and-resume pattern. When available page height is exhausted mid-story, the packager emits a FrozenStoryPackager for the current-page content and creates a new StoryPackager for the continuation. Any floats that straddle the break become carry-over obstacles, registered at Y 0 on the next page so text continues to wrap around their remaining height correctly. Story-absolute images past the break are re-included in the continuation children and re-anchored at their story coordinates adjusted by the split offset.",
            "keepWithNext": false,
            "kind": "flow-block",
            "overflowPolicy": "clip",
            "pageBreakBefore": false,
            "source": {
              "path": "elements[2].children[21]"
            },
            "sourceType": "p",
            "style": {
              "allowLineSplit": true,
              "marginBottom": 8,
              "orphans": 2,
              "widows": 2
            }
          },
          {
            "allowLineSplit": true,
            "content": "The architecture keeps all story-local coordinates intact across the split. A float anchored on page one whose bottom extends onto page two simply reappears at the top of page two with its remaining height, and text wraps around that carry-over obstacle just as it did on the first page. No special cases, no re-layout of previously rendered content — the SpatialMap and the stateful resolver handle it transparently, treating the carry-over as just another registered obstacle at Y 0.",
            "keepWithNext": false,
            "kind": "flow-block",
            "overflowPolicy": "clip",
            "pageBreakBefore": false,
            "source": {
